The government wants to limit the torture of “witches,” as it published in a pamphlet
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually of advanced age, cannot work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who become witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer such a bell."
“It is also not isolated to healthy young women, because they help in the work and have children,” explains a nun who, in the state capital of West Africa Burkina Faso, occupies a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an information booklet that should help prevent witch hunts.
However, this has a stick.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso don’t know how to read,” warns the journal Die Standard about the disadvantages of written sensitization.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, a neighboring Burkina Faso, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate accumulation of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman was trapped in the oil used for ritual anointings.
He was caught in flames when the group wanted to “throw out the bad spirits” of the woman.
The isolation of the “witches” is supported by people of all educational levels.
The Der Standard newspaper quoted a 42-year-old Burkina Faso businessman as saying: “Human soul eaters have always been a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to pacify the witch hunt, in the Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
Gambian President Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a wide-ranging witch hunt that allegedly had been related to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself by means of black magic.
“To help him he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, were forcibly taken randomly chosen men and women from among the Gambian peoples to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
In the farm, the arrested people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that also caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested did not survive the stay on the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand detainees.
Bakala’s tenant: heats up with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The man, of advanced age and shyness, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the company RPG Byty of the "carbon magnate" Zde<0xC5><0x88>ek Bakala, the largest private owner of flats for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried some documents with the new three-story leases: his, his daughter's and his son's, who is serving a sentence.
All three of them have just been caught up in the liberalization of rents.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns per month, the child will pay 4,100 crowns from next year for a two-bedroom apartment with a second-class separate kitchen.
“Furthermore, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler,” shows the man with his finger in his son’s new contract, over which he has full powers.
“But I signed it,” he explains, half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants do not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, the date on which they will publish a guide informing about how to proceed in these cases.
But in the face of this, man only makes a pledge.
“Everyone says one thing,” he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a great laboratory for testing liberalization.
After New Year will happen with the vast majority of the flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
Therefore, Aktualn<0xC4><0x9B>.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of the four in Ostrava and, Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to it a machine to pick up number.
"Rentaler 2011", can be read in a bright button of your touch screen.
When you press it, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
Almost no time to read "157" and the number already appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in the queue.
Soon after, an advanced marriage arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, as in the past: settlement requests, insurance issues, and similar issues.
The letters with the new leases will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of the tenants of the majority of the 44,000 floors belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty offers a 15 to 38% increase in rent on the cards.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
“It’s been running for a week, so it’s starting,” the workers who are in it when the client presents themselves as a journalist, after briefly doubting it, respond.
The liberalization and the old mining floors of Bakala are the most delicate topics in the area.
Before the elections, they were already dealt with high and clear by the Deputy President of Parliament, Ostrava-born Lubom<0xC3><0xAD>r Zaor<0xC3><0xA1>lek of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSD, and now appear continuously in the newspapers in the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
“I didn’t even change the damn bathroom plate,” the man mentioned in the introduction said.
According to the workers, for the moment they are more than retired to check if they receive a rental discount if they sign on time, as promised by the special RPG offer.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15 will also receive half of the February rental discount.
However, the window of the mining “liberalization” certainly does not manage to dispel the avalanche of doubt.
“Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only asked about the rent in 2011 about forty or fifty people,” the window employee estimates.
In the meantime, RPG proposes on the web and in its tables to hold individual meetings about contracts when necessary.
If the two parties fail to reach an agreement on the lease, an independent judge will have to resolve the matter.
“It’s not a threat, it’s information about the only possible way to proceed and completely in accordance with the law,” RPG warns in its pages.
“No one is going to be judged here,” says one of Byty’s RPG employees and a man standing on the street in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the reason.
“I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means of going to court,” he says.
But, immediately, the employee raises the doubt.
"We'll see."
“Mr. Zaor<0xC3><0xA1>lek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait,” he said.
Rental regulation will cease to exist in the majority of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
“Current rentals still do not even cover the amounts needed to maintain the community fund,” recalls Pavel Klime<0xC5><0xA1>, director of the residential portfolio of RPG Byty, who adds that the careless state of the community fund that angers tenants is the main rent for the owners.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPGs were able to invest in apartments with rents four billion, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the seats in the waiting room, now repeats some data that stand out in red.
“The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties.”
“Furthermore, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech crowns per square meter per month,” it is stated on the screen.
Only increased by 38% the rent of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
“In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts, of 19.66 crowns per square meter,” says RPG.
On 2,600 floors, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalization will not impact rents by a blow, but will escalate between four and eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent increase (see the chart) again on the floors, mainly in savings in heating: new windows and heating.
People who sign the lease agreement will have priority.
Architects have understood that offices also need daycare.
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that they also hide inside a small nursery with everything their own to such facilities: color walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can come to her.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, whose study went out of numerous well-known buildings in Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guardry.
The company employs about 90 people, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, the nursery is one of the benefits offered by Arch.Design to its workers as part of its social program.
The builders and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-guardry was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of the management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-guardry is funded through the European Social Fund within the framework of the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment, as well as the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (a endowment of more than 2.8 million Czech crowns) they were able to buy the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When you run out of funding (two years), the company Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the mini-guardry running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the company Economy Rating contributed to the submission of the funding application.
The attention of children is in the hands of qualified staff; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The nursery currently welcomes children without age limit, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since it is a "mini-guardian", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with the shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to adapt to the needs of the parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is individual education and care, the contents of the mini-guardian program are comparable to the usual pre-school education program.
In it children not only play, but also receive a quality education: from basic learning to preparation for school, they teach to English.
The class not only has toys and table games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up late school children when they are away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive while they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is located among the companies sign that they offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened personnel marketing.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Observe the interiors of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>
The roof looks like the tail of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remember the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Because of its shape similar to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the innovative use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of the scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
The cover of the house plays with dreamy lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, one observes a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought order.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, as it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentia and the torsion of forms continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the railings, the decorations of the doors, the mirrors and the signs.
The Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, located in the Eixample neighborhood at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA1>cia, emerged from the remodeling of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s idea of making a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> alone.
The architect Josep Mar<0xC3><0xAD>a Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their plans of the project came ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
On the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Mil<0xC3><0xA1> and the Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> G<0xC3><0xBC>ell Park, in which other pieces of it are found.
Due to its organic form, the locals soon after its completion named it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it "the house of the bushes".
It is also said that, at the height of the construction, the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motifs.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> projected into the house a unique system for the central heating era with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange to see his forty-five-degree inclination.
During construction, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> did not respect at all the building rules of the time and was not influenced by them.
Still, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although obviously in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years after its completion, the town hall was so impacted with the result that it requested to be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather on the contrary: just fifteen days after the city council’s request, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> applied for (and obtained) permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery of the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, of six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase leading up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the halls and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>, not only got a new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> plays with the light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and tragaluces.
The game with the two colors brings the maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits, they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and the bush, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entrance of other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> buildings in the city.
