The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new ways of life on Earth and possibly on other planets.
Although the researchers discovered the curious bacteria here on Earth, they say it demonstrates that there may be life forms without the main elements they considered essential.
"This organism has a double capacity."
"It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
“That makes it something very peculiar, although it hardly needs to be a really ‘alien’ way of life,” said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report appearing in the online edition of Thursday’s Science publication.
It has long been considered that there are six major elements essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, researchers have found that the bacterium, found in Mono Lake, California, may continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“It makes you wonder what else is possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the finding is important for the search for life on different planets on Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know the aspect it has.
