However, the call for a press conference to discuss it, in which details of the discovery were not disclosed, generated great speculation on the Internet about the possibility of the report indicating the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "yes shows is that in other planetary environments, there could be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of "standard" elements that we consider essential to life may not be as fixed," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
“This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element for another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure,” Cockell added.
The discovery was not made by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA’s Institute of Astrobiology, which led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace one another.
“Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus.”
"As a result, it can be difficult for organisms to differentiate them."
“However, arsenic is different enough that it doesn’t work as well as phosphorus, so it enters and, to put it in some way, it appeals to biochemical machinery,” explains Anbar.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they were able to adapt to and use to grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that there can naturally exist a life form that uses arsenic, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is most common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but an example has never been found to prove it works.
Arsenic was more common in the early ages of the Earth, he noted, so researchers speculated that early life forms may have used it.
“It does suggest that there could be other means of generating life, not just the way life was formed on Earth in the past,” said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
