A more moderate side of order maintenance is promoted in China
As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin marked the step in a city square, severely inspecting the nervous people in charge, issuing low-pitched orders with military authority.
He wanted the female members of the chengguan, the corpulent police officers of China’s urban order, feared and despised by their capricious energetic measures and their inclination to violence, to communicate a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"Signs!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "How beautiful are the girls!"
Four girls who barely passed adolescence with white gloves and identical olive green jackets and tight pants to draw attention.
Four pairs of perfectly aligned black shoes.
Four elegant hats perfectly placed on top of hair tied with blue and white striped cuffs.
“Personally, I think they have a normal appearance,” Mr. Tang said, disdainfully.
“The models are beautiful.”
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China’s urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have a degree.
The province of Guangdong changed the grayish green color of the uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating looks: in 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a snack cart, and observed it with the frown constantly for half an hour, until the walker picked up his things and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 people in Chengdu, has chosen a radical change of image.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police force, specifically chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the tough police a softer, feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China’s slightest respect for these city squads.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only allowed to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But Chinese news media routinely portrays a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei Province shot and killed a passerby after using his cell phone to film them while dissolving a protest against a waste dump.
Last year, a Beijing inspector training manual was stolen and published on the internet, in which it was described as effectively beating criminals without causing them to bleed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon walker suffered brain damage after a row with five officers.
A violent video game, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
“Chengguan has left a scar on the government,” lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper called for "a really meticulous cleaning".
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
After the district requested through a notice eight new female recruits in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News asked whether women had real duties or were simply a stage distraction.
The answer seems to be a bit of both.
The district's notice called for female candidates aged 18 to 22, with a good figure "and the five harmonious facial features".
They should have a height above average, greater than 1.6 meters or 5 feet, 2 1<0xE2><0x81><0x84>2 inches.
Withdrawal at the age of 26 is mandatory.
