Can civility stretch a bridge to unite divisions?
After a notable campaign for invective and negativity, a bit of civility has been unleashed this week in Washington.
Is it a premonition of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no progress on the major issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But as everyone says, it was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two parties, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to earn partisan points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit committee was equally civilised, despite the political differences between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is just enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a trial period, probing each other to identify signs of cooperativeism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
The reason why Tuesday’s meeting and subsequent evaluations by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too big and they are too deep-rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two sides are on opposite sides.
However, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
“There’s no doubt that things have changed regarding the way things are said,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“They are inevitable after the election.
The elections arouse partisan passions, which then become extinct.
That's good."
In some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to widening unemployment subsidies, probably because Republicans cannot make them believe they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying the unemployment subsidy for the unemployed.
Following Tuesday’s meeting at the White House, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston, of the Brookings Institution, warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continuous bipartisanism when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He said, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement begins.
“After the things that must be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to a confrontational one,” he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civility can lead to true cooperation.
“I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a test for the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who decisively contributed to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut state spending and repeal the new health law.
Those lines of support are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Commission, which include reform of the tax code and the increase in some taxes and retirement age, and the reduction of expenses.
Co-Presidents Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have been in charge of one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forcibly introduced the issue of deficit in the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member committee to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the elected officials on the panel, suggesting that in tax matters there are, at least at present, little basis or desire for commitment.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans of the White House and those of Congress.
The first will take place next year in the form of partisan shocks, when Republicans challenge Obama over budget, taxes and medical assistance, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a dead end, as happened in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the people.
Anyone who thinks they are losing is likely to change course and look for commitment.
However, this can be an optimistic view.
Partisanism and polarization are now larger than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans in Congress than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
A leaked U.S. document portrays Moscow as a haven of corruption
The city’s control is in the hands of a “cleptocracy,” and leaves a portion of the bribes and protection money that collects directly from the Kremlin, the U.S. Embassy in Russia reported in February.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service handle huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal groups.
Each stratum of the bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the “vertical authority”, takes its part as the money goes up the scale.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and blames him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a cleanup since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a major construction company, have systematically denied allegations of corruption over the years, and he has won several libel lawsuits over such allegations.
In September, when asked on a Russian television channel about a documentary that suggested it was corrupt, he said, "It's crazy, it's crazy, it's annoying."
According to the polls, the Russians overwhelmingly believe that their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find the details explained in detail, as they were in the embassy report, and it is unheard of for diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
"The direct links of the Moscow city government to criminality have led some to call it 'disfunctional', and to claim that the government works more like a kleptocracy than like a government," the statement said.
“The criminal elements enjoy a ‘krysha’ (a term of the criminal world and the mafia that literally means ‘roof’ or protection) that transfers the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor’s office, as well as all sectors of the bureaucracy of the Mos government.
"Analysts identify a three-tiered structure in Moscow's criminal world."
"Luzhkov is at the highest."
"The SFS, MVD and militia are on the second level."
“Finally, common criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level.”
“This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a gap in some areas, because the city does not provide some services.”
The report states that the SFS collects money from larger companies, and that the police target small businesses.
One source, the report said, “explained that Moscow’s business owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and SFS (rather than organized crime groups) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but are also protected by law.”
“For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority.”
The note notes that while the collection of money is complete, protection may be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who don’t pay quickly find their businesses closed by one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has confessed that he has made little progress.
The embassy note reports men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, inside the Kremlin itself.
“In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to trust the bureaucrats,” said Georgy Satarov, director of the Indem expert group in Moscow, in a recent interview.
“But he is a part of this bureaucracy.”
“He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia.”
Without politics, without opposition, without a separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
At the national level, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
In a recent survey on global perceptions of corruption conducted by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked No. 154 (countries are classified from least to most corrupt).
The disclosure of the U.S. Embassy note, which did not occur until late at Moscow’s hour, will surely cause disgust within the Russian government, and even though Luzhkov may be blamed for Moscow’s weaknesses, could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed to CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested that WikiLeaks documents could be lies and reacted furiously by a revelation that claimed that American diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
“The truth of the matter is that this relates to our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policies in this country,” he said.
“But to be honest with you, we don’t suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it would have been done in such an immoral way.”
Veterans of the Red Jemeres forced to face the past
In a dimly lit concrete classroom, with stained and peeled walls, the director of Anlong Veng High School recalled the man who had built it, the last leader of the Ta Mok Red Jemeres.
“Everyone here loves Ta Mok.”
“He was a good leader and he cared about his people,” said 42-year-old Sring Kor Ma.
Known as "The Butcher" for his brutality during the government of the Red Jemeres, the commander remains popular in this remote former Red Jemeres fortress in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where thousands of former soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-held loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to publicly confront people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed here a high school textbook that for the first time teaches the history of the Red Jemeres to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a United Nations-Cambodia mixed court issued the first conviction of a former member of the Khmer Rouge, sentencing the former head of the notorious Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among Anlong Veng Red Jemer veterans, complicating efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Red Jemers, but they can do nothing,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization that investigates the regime.
“For them, life under the Red Jemers was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.”
“This is generating divisions within families.”
During the reign of the Khmer Rouge, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease, or overwork.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the government led by Pol Pot, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and jungles of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country’s first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Red Jemer fighters began to defect to the government, culminating in the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieuphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of its benefactors, the oldest fighters of the Red Jemer fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few elite Red Jemerese officials retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their weapons, the racial soldiers remain poor and unskilled farmers.
“These people have gained little profit after surrender,” said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums across Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They have incorporated the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
“They were raised with no concept of doing business.”
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Red Jemers when he was a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before devoting himself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
“Life with the Red Jemeres was fine,” he said.
"Ta Mok gave him to eat everyone."
“But now life is hard because we have to self-sustain.”
The current Khmer Rouge court has also raised concerns here.
Earlier this year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former minister of the Red Jemer.
The court’s mandate is to prosecute leading leaders and those more responsible for crimes, but it has not said whether it will pursue cases in addition to those four.
This did not serve much to calm fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on 64-year-old Im Chaem, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the reign of the Red Jemeres in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Center that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced workers are thought to have died.
During a recent stormy afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his home on wooden pilots on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows on the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Red Jemeres.
She claimed that if the court called her she would not be presented.
“Cambodia is at peace and stable,” he said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Red Jemers in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court pursues more suspects, although experts and historians question it.
“Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past,” he said.
But facing the past is exactly what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the Documentation Center.
“The reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to reunite the broken pieces,” he said.
“It is our duty to gather these broken pieces so that we can understand.”
The center produced the first government-approved text book on the Red Jemeres, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", of 75 pages.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education’s high school history textbook, which contains less than four pages on the Red Jemeres.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know few details about the Red Jemer, despite the city's link to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he took the book home to study.
“My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court,” he said.
“They have suspicions because they are not sure about the number of people the court will prosecute.”
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the textbook and the court are beginning to produce an impact, he said.
However, here the Red Jemeres retain a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a road with too many weeds and covered with discarded plastic bags leads to a rectangle of the black hollin covered by an oxidized roof of tin.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a lot of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a cell phone salesman on the side of the road, said he didn’t know much about the man who was cremated there.
“But he has a strong spirit and many locals go there to pray,” he said.
It was Nuom Sothea’s birthday, and later that day he decided to walk to the place of Pol Pot’s last rest, where he would leave a handful of mature bananas in the hope of good luck.
