How should these movements be interpreted?
It goes without saying that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another twist in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which collides with keeping the old traditions of much of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany begins to speculate about the three possible exits to the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, although now seems science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with the German proposals of greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigor, fines to the transgressing countries, possible suspensions of payments of some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission stimulated deficits, the German government pulled out of the manga a constitutional reform to prevent them from starting in 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (plans of fiscal rigor and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second on the front gave it to the Central European country when Merkel painfully extended Greece’s bailout decision.
Already then it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion and the published one were very against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the Union treaties, to make possible the salvation of a country and, at the same time, to force private lenders to run with part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should be attending the process of reforming the Union that will make those measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it is telling us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we may not agree very well, from that date the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which the offender countries will be severely punished, may be forced to declare themselves in suspension of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also run with part of the cost.
Germany is pointing out to us that we must follow a severe path of growth with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not tolerate it.
The invitation is clear.
And we'd be wrong not to understand it.
It’s not just about resuming the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they demand from us is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that current turbulence will lead to greater peace of mind.
And let us take advantage of the window of opportunity that they have given us, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood this and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with the big companies and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite criticism of Merkel, the thesis has opened the way for a home order.
But the red line that Germany has drawn there is, and it doesn’t seem like they’re going to move it.
And, among the possibilities that are contemplated, that of leaving a monetary zone too crowded with unserious countries cannot be excluded.
Then Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sport and Fraud Law
Trets like those of Alonso and Ramos before the Ajax show ingenuity but unwillingness to escape a sanction.
The expulsion allegedly struck by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match played on 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether or not such behavior is anti-sporting and if, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is well known, after a few minutes to finish the game (which his team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately wasted time on taking missing paths to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will end up as leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction of the next match of the league, against the Auxerre, and will be able to pass clean cards to the next stage.
Finally, the UEFA discipline committee has sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and different economic amounts to the players involved.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or the like is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the rules not written, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the reported case is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem presumes of nobility and honor, and which in the past has fined its players for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who has a history of more than one.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions are committed by fraud of law; in fact, they are actions respectful of the sport regulation, but seem to elude its meaning.
The issue is to examine the type of damage that causes the sports spirit.
One of the assets that the sports spirit understands is the physical integrity of the opposing players, which with these actions was not jeopardized, i.e. there was no violent game.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with clean play is to prevent the team of the infringing players from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
Now, the paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it did not fit what we normally characterize as cheating or law fraud, because their violation of the rules was not made hidden to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely their action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders get in the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that it is not put in a disadvantage to the opponent or profit in the same game, since obviously the result of the action is to leave the team itself with fewer players.
And it is also not a useful strategy for the next game, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that may threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, as the team can be eliminated at the first exchange, and in addition with this performance players fulfill a penalty match and pass to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, going through rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the spirit of sport, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that make the most of what the rules allow.
In our case, players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without winning the punishment or running away from it.
Although the border between ingenuity and fraud law is diffuse, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was two self-exclusions and the way in which the transmission of the directive was carried out to provoke them.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as aesthetic.
