In fact, he said, over the past four years, his country has invested $245 million in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made it clear that China will not change its objectives, but will continue to work together with the international community on this issue.
He noted that the Chinese strategy on climate change is divided into four sections: dialogue; capacity building; institution building and pilot programme support.
In all of these areas, progress has been made, including last year's adoption of a new Energy Law, which sets out the objectives of reducing gas emissions, he explained.
On the other hand, he stressed that in China, federal authorities have been working in a coordinated way with state and local authorities to achieve the goals of energy saving, efficient energy use and emission reduction.
In addition, he said, several multi-year plans are underway or have already been completed, both funded by the Chinese government and by governments from other countries.
For example, he reported, the Energy Efficient Use Program, which was implemented over the past five years and which received investments from the United Nations (UN), government and private initiative.
A provincial climate change project is also underway, another for the change of incandescent focus by savers and another for mitigation and adaptation, he said.
