EU changes rules to get visa
People must go to the Visa Application Service Centers prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower as well as the waiting time.
Starting January 10, 2011, the procedure for processing a visa at the U.S. Embassy and consulates will be changed.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicant Service Centers (ASC) before their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take biometric information from the applicant, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, you will no longer need to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another one for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a one-time payment covering all three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas on request (including temporary worker visas) and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Because biometric information will be taken at the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in this less time than in the past.
Likewise, those applying for visas at the Consulates in Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For additional information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
