A Global Plan to Renovate Lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in a hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHGs) in an amount that corresponds to almost a third of the additional decrease that must be carried out to stabilize the planet’s climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of major concrete projects that the UN expects to be adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, even better, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), much of the 1.8 billion tons of emiluminated (Gt) of the planet would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the planetary automotive park.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of that amount should be further reduced to stabilize, by 2020, the increase in temperatures by two degrees centigrade to prevent it from being out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is further reduced by twice.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which allows us to make an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
Above, they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have expressed their reservations regarding the fluocompact bulbs, since they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers place instructions.
However, the report states, the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not the fluocompact bulbs, but the coal thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that is shed with the incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the advantages this international program would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save a billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, i.e. the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion.
