The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little anxiety) the head of the secret services (if it could not be, I know, editor of the Liberation), who only considers certain what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same one that Newsweek published last week.
So why has the revelations of these records caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that the embassies, at least since World War II and since the Heads of State can call or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for some limited exercise of representation, have been transformed into centres of pilgrimage.
Any viewer who watches research films knows it perfectly, we just seem to not know it by hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secretive country in the world significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the “convicts”.
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell’s time, he could conceive of himself to all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it now happens, that not even the crypts of the secrets of power can escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, elected as the revenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can you hold on to a power that can no longer keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without a secret, since it comes from the public domain; but it means that the secret is to reveal everything that has been done by Hill.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and much more, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, since it would be like publishing it in a street sign.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, you can’t expect to keep confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has moved on a plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my prediction is a matter of science fiction and therefore novel, but I imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, by the way, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
That information is then preserved, in a single copy, in locked drawers: after all, the attempt to spy on the Watergate was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is currently advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a wired telegraph (telephone).
The (analog) video tapes had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, advancing and retreating, discovering all the secrets of assembly, while now the (digital) CDs only allow to advance or retreat from chapter to chapter, i.e., at enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the trips it takes, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary that politics and communication techniques take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was secretly going on in the embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies that ask for confidential information to the press.
Climate: France’s caps on its funding promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unblocked financing promises (called fast start or early) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French hats have been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion in three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.260 million (i.e. 420 million a year).
During the opening of the COP16, the EU has put its best cards on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its member states, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was appreciable and was appreciated for what it really is: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
Under the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what is meant by “new and additional”.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
At present, each one chooses the reference that suits him best.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as its reference year: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years in terms of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references as regards the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 are "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditure of previous years or to the total level of official development aid.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while it intends to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the division between donations and loans.
Again, there are no rules and each one chooses the method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that each euro borrowed is equivalent to a donated euro.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions based on more effective technologies), it is necessary to present a euro that is to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... As a whole, only the cost of the loan should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it “respects” its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); consult the EU document to see for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to meet its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast-start financing, France commits a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other hand, in relation to real financial effort.
Spending just <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has taken care of the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can just lend?) and in the negotiations, as developing countries are not stupid...
The early funding chapter is a minuscule, relatively short-term, in relation to the overall climate negotiations.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNCITRAL.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could advance the debate on gambling in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter that is currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
Therefore, we have the hope of the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of “additional character” and the use of loans would help improve the level of international confidence needed to advance the negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Genérations Futures (the old movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem dealt with", acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that a child of about ten years old usually consumes at four meals and a tent.
These meals taken as a model, which comply with official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day), as well as treats, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five are classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EDs), according to studies from various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
“Although, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is worrisome,” the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogens and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a banned fungicide in France.
The same applies to Kenya’s green Jews, including in food, where the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the Russian fillet, canned tuna and even the bread bar or gum were bonded with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, the analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most "nutritive" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the plastic dish analysis used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk that these “contaminants cocktails” generate for the consumer is “probably underestimated,” the study says.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed to "face the gravity of the situation" apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase of diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EASA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
